      <intermediateExchange id="891d8978-d71d-59c2-b55d-03b66c58e446" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" casNumber="010026-13-8" amount="1.42956573262103" intermediateExchangeId="b2a4e23e-4a1a-4def-890f-e08adee40333" activityLinkId="4c8dd6cb-ae54-5912-aeae-71fbefb3d353">
        <name xml:lang="en">phosphorus pentachloride</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Calculated value based on stoichiometric calculations and literature data. 
208.237262g/mol is the molar mass of phosphorus pentachloride (PCl5). 
153.331262g/mol is the molar mass of phosphorus oxychloride (POCl3). 

The industrial production of phospofurs oxchloride is done either in batch or continuous process by the direct reaction of excess sulfur with phosphorus trichloride at about 180  degree C. Purification of the product can be done through distillation. Adding catalysts such as halides of aluminum, iron or disulfur dichloride both accelerates the reaction and decreases reaction temperatures. Alternatively thiophosphoryl chloride can be produced by reacting phosphorus pentachloride with phosphorus pentasulfide, or phosphorus pentachloride with antimony trisulfide (Bettermann et al., 2000)

Chemical reaction: PCl5 + NaCl + 2 HNaO → POCl3 + 3 Na + 3 Cl, the assumed efficiency is 0.95.</comment>
        <uncertainty>
          <lognormal meanValue="1.42956573262103" mu="0.35737071466885245" variance="0.0006" varianceWithPedigreeUncertainty="0.010025"/>
          <pedigreeMatrix reliability="2" completeness="3" temporalCorrelation="2" geographicalCorrelation="2" furtherTechnologyCorrelation="3"/>
        </uncertainty>
